<p><a name="Notes_and_references" id="Notes_and_references"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Patriarchy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Notes and references">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Notes and references</span></h2>
<div class="references-small references-column-count references-column-count-2" style="-moz-column-count:2; column-count:2;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-Britannica-0">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Britannica_0-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Britannica_0-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Britannica_0-2" title=""><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book">"Matriarchy". <i>Encyclopædia Britannica</i>. 2007.  "The view of matriarchy as constituting a stage of cultural development is now generally discredited. Furthermore, the consensus among modern anthropologists and sociologists is that a strictly matriarchal society never existed.".</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Matriarchy&amp;rft.atitle=Encyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Patriarchy"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
