<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> "The first [state] is Paternity or Patriarchy, which was when a family growing so great as it could not containe it selfe within one habitation, some branches of the descendents were forced to plant themselves into new families." <i>Concerning the Post-Nati of Scotland</i> (1626), in <i>Three Speeches</i> (1641) (cited after <a href="/wiki/OED" title="OED" class="mw-redirect">OED</a>).</li>
<li id="cite_note-Sanderson-3">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Sanderson_3-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Sanderson_3-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFSanderson2001">Sanderson, Stephen K. (2001). <i>The Evolution of Human Sociality</i>. Rowman &amp; Littlefield. p.&#160;198.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Evolution+of+Human+Sociality&amp;rft.aulast=Sanderson&amp;rft.aufirst=Stephen+K.&amp;rft.au=Sanderson%2C+Stephen+K.&amp;rft.date=2001&amp;rft.pages=p.%26nbsp%3B198&amp;rft.pub=Rowman+%26+Littlefield&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Patriarchy"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
